<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-008-192 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 552 128</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Nov 25 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Australia: government extends &quot;buy Australian&quot; policy.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Zucker, Paul.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Government RegulationNational GovernmentImportAustraliaMarketing Strategy.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Australia: Government Extends &quot;Buy Australian&quot; Policy 11/25/91 CANBERRA,AUSTRALIA, 1991 NOV 25 (NB) -- &quot;Make it in Australia&quot; is the new campaigndesigned to get Australians to buy local products when they are at least asgood as imports.andP;  Launching the campaign Senator Bolkus said governmentspending in Australia exceeds AUS$30 billion per year, much of which was notcurrently being spent on local goods.andM;The first phase of the campaign last year was &quot;Offshore? What for?,&quot; and thisis claimed with making 30 percent of government buyers decide to buyAustralian where appropriate.andP;  Senator Bolkus said hisandM;department was tracking the import of components used in local manufacturing,and was able to advise local manufacturers how to source local componentswhere available.andP;  &quot;We're able put manufacturers together where appropriate,making local production more scale-effective.&quot;andM;The policy asks that all government buyers be prepared to buy the Australianor New Zealand product where it is cost, quality and service competitive.andP;  Hesaid that, taking after sales service into account, local products often hadan advantage anyway.andM;Other changes that make local purchases easier, is the relaxation of what noware seen to be unnecessary standards.andP;  &quot;We used to have a uniquespecification for government furniture.andP;  ManufacturersandM;who made to that specification could only practically sell to the government.andO;Now, the specification is in line with normal commercial furniture, somanufacturers have a much wider market to design and manufacture for.&quot;andM;He also said that previous government policy, while not encouragingandM;local production, did not discourage lazy local manufacturers.andP;  Now,andM;the government is actively looking for local suppliers, and asking &quot;can yousupply?&quot;.andM;(Paul Zucker/19911125/Contact: Purchase Australian Office, ph: andplus;61-2-906 2144fax: andplus;61-2-906 2172)</TEXT></DOC>